  "prompt": "Are Australian aboriginals descendants from people from Africa that left over 75,000 years ago?",
  "response": "Yes, Australian Aboriginals are descendants of early modern humans who migrated out of Africa tens of thousands of years ago. Genetic, archaeological, and anthropological evidence suggests that the ancestors of all modern non-African populations, including Australian Aboriginals, began migrating from Africa around 75,000 to 60,000 years ago.\n\nHere\u2019s a brief overview of the migratory path that led to the settlement of Australia:\n\n1. **Out of Africa Migration**: Around 75,000\u201360,000 years ago, a group of anatomically modern humans left Africa, likely via the Horn of Africa or the Bab-el-Mandeb Strait, and spread across the Arabian Peninsula and into South Asia.\n\n2. **Spread into Southeast Asia and Sahul**: From South Asia, these populations migrated eastward into Southeast Asia. Around 50,000\u201365,000 years ago, some of these groups ventured into Sahul, the ancient landmass that included modern-day Australia, New Guinea, and Tasmania, which were connected during periods of lower sea levels.\n\n3. **Settlement of Australia**: Archaeological evidence, such as the findings at sites like Lake Mungo in New South Wales, indicates that humans had likely arrived in Australia by at least 50,000 years ago, possibly earlier. Australian Aboriginals are considered one of the oldest continuous cultures in the world, with a lineage tracing back to these early settlers.\n\nGenetic studies of Aboriginal Australians, such as those involving mitochondrial DNA and Y-chromosome analysis, support this migration route and confirm their deep ancestral ties to the first human populations to leave Africa. This makes Aboriginal Australians one of the most ancient populations outside of Africa, with a rich cultural heritage spanning tens of thousands of years.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
